descript.abstract: Centerline 10.8 version for expanded area use, CAD applications, and framework for networking
descript.purpose: Provide enhanced centerline layer for streets, highways, paths, and transit
descript.supplinf: This is the final version of the RMSI Centerline 10 editied by Brian B. Quinn, Ph.D., GISP on 2009 01 09 This includes most of the requirements for networking, except for the overlay + creation of nodes for the rail lines. Attributes from Contra Costa county were joined from Alameda County Sherrif's street layers of 2008 08. Significant improvements to geometry were made in the Kensington area, and significant additions to streets in El Cerrito and Richmond Annex have been added. Significant improvements to the completeness of bay-side trails from Emeryville to Point Isabel have been added. Many refinements of CFCC codes have been made A new CATEGORY attribute has been added to simplify symbolization or definition query use.

overview.dsoverv: There are four fields related to traversal time, for every segment in the centerline network. Based on the direction that each segment was drawn, there is a FT_MINUTES, From-To time (car), TF_MINUTES,To-From time (car), FT_PEDESTRIAN, From-To time (ped), and TF_PEDESTRIAN, To-From time (ped). The times are crude, based on CFCC codes and speed limits. Lots and lots of room for refinement---but first someone had to care enough to put the effort in to get more real-world about it all. There are four fields so that you don't need to have a symmetrical time, as in peds are much slower going uphill.
